Amazon.com Delivers 50th Anniversary of DNA Celebration

Editor, Brooke Gilbert

FEATURED IN THIS E-MAIL:
* DNA Essentials
* Publisher Feature
* Stephen Jay Gould: Evolution's Champion
* Real-World Bioinformatics Computing

To discuss the next steps in the genomics revolution--and to
celebrate the 50th anniversary of the discovery of the structure of
DNA--"Time" magazine is convening The Future of Life Summit,
February 19-21, 2003, in Monterey, California. Innovators at the
vanguard of science and industry will interact with ethicists,
religious leaders, activists, and venture capitalists for a
provocative dialogue with "Time" editors about biotechnology and its
implications. Nobel Laureates James Watson and Hamilton Smith are
joined by Richard Dawkins, Matt Ridley, Bill Joy, Craig Venter,
Francis Collins, Dean Hamer, Richard Carmona, E.O. Wilson, Raymond
Kurzweil, Susan Greenfield, Juan Enriquez, Rudolph Tanzi, and scores
of others. Participation is limited, creating an environment for
personal interaction. For more information and to register, call
1-877-860-7697, or go to http://www.thefutureoflife.com.

Partnering with Amazon.com, "Time" magazine, along with its editors,
conference speakers, and advisory board members, has recommended a
stunning selection of books--from the classics to the cutting
edge--that explore all the topics surrounding this momentous
occasion. After you've browsed through these bestselling and
provocative titles, you can please your inner scientist further by
visiting our 50th Anniversary of DNA Store. --Brooke Gilbert

Super Saver Shipping 
Free on orders over $25. Some restrictions apply. See details:
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/subst/misc/super-saver-shipping.html/ref=mk_del_ssfs 

DNA ESSENTIALS
**************
"DNA: The Secret of Life"
James D. Watson
Our price: $27.97 | You save: $11.98
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0375415467/ref=mk_del_434213

Fifty years ago, James D. Watson, then just 24, helped launch the
greatest ongoing scientific quest of our time. Now, with unique
authority and sweeping vision, Watson gives us the first full
account of the genetic revolution--from Mendel's garden to the
double helix to the sequencing of the human genome and beyond.
Facing a future of choices and social and ethical implications we
dare not ignore, we could have no better guide than James Watson,
who leads us with the same bravura storytelling that made "The
Double Helix" one of the most successful books on science ever
published. Infused with a scientist's awe at nature's marvels and a
humanist's profound sympathies, "DNA" is destined to become the
classic telling of the defining scientific saga of our age. --From
the publisher, Alfred A. Knopf

"The Private Life of the Brain: Emotions, Consciousness, and the
Secret of the Self"
Susan A. Greenfield
Our price: $11.87 | You save: $5.08
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0471399752/ref=mk_del_434213

What's going on in there? One of the great scientific and
philosophical mysteries is how a few pounds of wet, salty cobwebs
can give rise to the rich experience that we call consciousness.
Oxford neuroscientist Susan Greenfield peers inside the dimly lit
skull to show us what she thinks is going on in "The Private Life of
the Brain." Greenfield has a facility for explaining tricky
scientific concepts in language that can engage any reader. She
presents the basics of contemporary thought on consciousness as they
relate to her own theory, which involves a continuum of experience
between sensual, emotional grounding in the surrounding world and
rational, cognitive withdrawal into mental life.

"Guiding Icarus : Merging Bioethics with Corporate Interests"
Rahul K. Dhanda
Our price: $34.95
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0471223808/ref=mk_del_434213

Dhanda (Business Development Division, Interleukin Genetics) offers
advice to biotechnology companies on avoiding bad publicity and
expensive lawsuits in pursuit of profiting off DNA manipulation and
other recent technologies. By adopting ethical considerations into
their corporate strategies, companies will avoid the worst effects
of the controversies over these technologies, argues Dhanda.
Separate chapters focus on the controversies arising from
genetically modified food, DNA data banking, personalized medicine,
and stem cell research.

"Enough : Setting Limits on Human Genetic Technology"
Bill McKibben
Our price: $17.50 | You save: $7.50
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0805070966/ref=mk_del_434213

From the bestselling author of "The End of Nature" comes a
passionate plea to limit the technologies that could change the very
definition of who we are. We are on the verge of crossing the line
from born to made, from created to built. Sometime in the next few
years, a scientist will reprogram a human egg or sperm cell,
spawning a genetic change that could be passed down into eternity.
We are sleepwalking toward the future, argues Bill McKibben, and
it's time to open our eyes. Nearly 15 years ago, in The End of
Nature, McKibben demonstrated that humanity had begun to irrevocably
alter--and endanger--our environment on a global scale. Now, in
"Enough: Setting Limits on Human Genetic Technology," he turns his
eye to an array of technologies that could change our relationship
not with the rest of nature, but with ourselves.

"The Journey of Man: A Genetic Odyssey"
Spencer Wells
Our price: $20.97 | You save: $8.98
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/069111532X/ref=mk_del_434213

Spencer Wells traces human evolution back to our very first
ancestor in "The Journey of Man." Along the way, Wells sums up the
explosive effect of new techniques in genetics on the field of
evolutionary biology and all available evidence from the fossil
record. Wells's seemingly sexist title is purposeful: he argues that
the Y chromosome gives us a unique opportunity to follow our
migratory heritage back to a sort of Adam, just as earlier work in
mitochondrial DNA allowed the identification of Eve, mother of all
Homo sapiens. While his descriptions of the advances made by such
eminent scientists as Richard Lewontin and Luigi Luca Cavalli-Sforza
can be dry, Wells comes through with sparkling metaphors when it
counts, as when he compares genetic drift to a bouillabaisse recipe
handed down through a village's generations.

"The Selfish Gene"
Richard Dawkins
Our price: $10.47 | You save: $4.48
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0192860925/ref=mk_del_434213

Inheriting the mantle of revolutionary biologist from Darwin,
Watson, and Crick, Richard Dawkins forced an enormous change in the
way we see ourselves and the world with the publication of "The
Selfish Gene." Suppose, instead of thinking about organisms using
genes to reproduce themselves, as we had since Mendel's work was
rediscovered, we turn it around and imagine that "our" genes build
and maintain us in order to make more genes. That simple reversal
seems to answer many puzzlers that had stumped scientists for years,
and we haven't thought of evolution in the same way since.

More recommended titles:

* "Genome" by Matt Ridley
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0060932902/ref=mk_del_434213

* "Watson and DNA: Making a Scientific Revolution" by Victor K.
McElheny
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0738203416/ref=mk_del_434213

* "The Blind Watchmaker: Why the Evidence of Evolution Reveals a
Universe Without Design" by Richard Dawkins
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393315703/ref=mk_del_434213

* "Redesigning Humans: Our Inevitable Genetic Future" by Gregory
Stock
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/061806026X/ref=mk_del_434213

* "Guns, Germs, and Steel: The Fates of Human Societies" by Jared
Diamond
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393317552/ref=mk_del_434213

Visit the 50th Anniversary of DNA Store
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/browse/-/3118561/ref=mk_del_434213

Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory Press

In addition to "Abraham Lincoln's DNA and Other Adventures in
Genetics," Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory Press publishes resources
on molecular and cell biology, genetics, cancer, microbiology,
development, and neuroscience, written and edited by distinguished
scientists throughout the world. 

PUBLISHER FEATURE
*****************
Academic Press DNA Bookshelf

For nearly 60 years, Academic Press has been serving the
information needs of scientists, researchers, engineers, and other
professionals in industry and academia. Amazon.com has partnered
with Academic Press to gather a list of their bestselling DNA books.

Read more
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/feature/-/434240/ref=del_434213
 
STEPHEN JAY GOULD: EVOLUTION'S CHAMPION
***************************************
Stephen Jay Gould was one of the great theorists and popularizers
of modern biology and an outspoken champion of science. His last
book, "The Structure of Evolutionary Theory," is a huge manifesto
revising and defining Darwin's principles. Gould was a prolific
writer and editor, with more than 20 books to his name. Here are
some of our favorites:

1. "The Mismeasure of Man" (1981) is Gould's scathing scientific
indictment of both the intelligence-testing industry and the class
system that is structured around it.
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393314251/ref=mk_del_434213

2. "Wonderful Life: The Burgess Shale and the Nature of History"
(1989) uses the strange fossils of a famous 600-million-year-old
formation to make a case for his controversial stance on contingent
evolution. Sounds dry, but it's not--Gould is at his best when
showing his love of science.
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/039330700X/ref=mk_del_434213

3. "The Book of Life" (1993), edited by Gould, offers a beautifully
illustrated overview of the history of life as told in the fossil
record. An excellent general reference.
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393321568/ref=mk_del_434213

4. "Rocks of Ages" (1999) marks Gould's efforts to reconcile science
and religion. He recognizes the majesty of both without trying to
blur the line between them.
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/034545040X/ref=mk_del_434213

5. "The Lying Stones of Marrakech" (2000) is, as the subtitle says,
Gould's second-to-last collection of essays from his popular series
in "Natural History" magazine.
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0609807552/ref=mk_del_434213 

REAL-WORLD BIOINFORMATICS COMPUTING
***********************************
Here are some recommended books to help you find the biological
information you've been hunting for:

* "Beginning Perl for Bioinformatics" by James Tisdall
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0596000804/ref=mk_del_434213

* "Bioinformatics: A Practical Guide to the Analysis of Genes and
Proteins, Second Edition" by Andreas D. Baxevanis and B.F. Francis
Ouellette
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0471383910/ref=mk_del_434213

* "Developing Bioinformatics Computer Skills" by Cynthia Gibas and
Per Jambeck
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1565926641/ref=mk_del_434213

* "Bioinformatics: Sequence and Genome Analysis" by David W. Mount
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0879696087/ref=mk_del_434213

* "Computational Molecular Biology: An Introduction" by Peter Clote
and Rolf Backofen
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0471872520/ref=mk_del_434213

Wiley Presents: Bioinformatics Tools

From bioinformatics to genomics and proteomics, Wiley offers
scientists the tools they need to confidently delve deeper into
their research and branch into new areas of exploration. Wiley's
authors--all leaders and innovators in the scientific research
community from around the world--are experts in their fields,
providing you with their own first-hand experiences and
perspectives.

Read more
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/feature/-/394746/ref=del_434213

Shop for more bioinformatics titles
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/browse/-/760204/ref=mk_del_434213 

