	<img src="http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0192860925.01.__PE30_PIm.arrow,TopLeft,-2,-19_SCTZZZZZZZ_.jpg" width=76 height=116 align=top border=0></a>

</td>

<td valign=top>
<table border=0>
	<tr><td colspan=2>
	<b>
	<a href=http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0192860925/ref=mk_del_434213_87>
	<i>The Selfish Gene</i></a> &nbsp;&nbsp;</b>
	  
<img src="http://g-images.amazon.com/images/G/01/icons/icon-books.gif" width=22 height=22  align=absmiddle hspace=2 vspace=2 border=0  alt=Icon ><br>
	by Richard Dawkins<br clear=left>
	
		 Inheriting the mantle of revolutionary biologist
						from Darwin, Watson, and Crick, Richard 
Dawkins forced an enormous change in
						the way we see ourselves and the world with 
the publication of 
						
<A href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0192860925/ref=mk_del_434213_88"><i>The 
Selfish
						Gene</i></A>. Suppose, instead of thinking 
about organisms using genes
						to reproduce themselves, as we had since 
Mendel's work was rediscovered, we
						turn it around and imagine that "our" genes 
build and maintain us in order to
						make more genes. That simple reversal seems 
to answer many puzzlers that had
						stumped scientists for years, and we haven't 
thought of evolution in the same
						way since.<p>
	
	</td></tr>

		<tr>
		<td width=50% valign=top colspan=2>
		 
